  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Education system of India before the arrival of Britishers?",
  "response": "Before the arrival of the British, the education system in India was diverse, deeply rooted in its cultural and religious traditions, and primarily centered around local and community-based learning. It was largely informal and decentralized, with various systems catering to different sections of society. Here\u2019s an overview of the education system in pre-colonial India:\n\n---\n\n### **1. Gurukul System**\n- The **Gurukul** system was one of the oldest and most prominent educational systems in India.\n- Students lived with their guru (teacher) in an ashram or gurukul, where they received education in various subjects.\n- The curriculum included the **Vedas**, **Upanishads**, philosophy, grammar, mathematics, astronomy, warfare, and ethics.\n- Education was holistic, focusing not only on intellectual development but also on physical, moral, and spiritual growth.\n- This system was primarily accessible to the upper castes, particularly Brahmins.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Buddhist and Jain Education**\n- Buddhist monasteries (**Viharas**) and Jain centers were important educational institutions.\n- Subjects like philosophy, logic, medicine, and literature were taught.\n- Education was available to all sections of society, including women and lower castes.\n- Nalanda, Takshashila, and Vikramashila were renowned Buddhist universities that attracted students from across Asia.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Local and Vocational Education**\n- Vocational education was imparted through apprenticeships in crafts, trade, and skills.\n- Artisans, farmers, and craftsmen learned their trades informally through family and community traditions.\n- Education was practical and skill-based, tailored to the needs of daily life and economic activities.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Islamic Influence (Post-12th Century)**\n- With the arrival of Islamic rulers, **Madrasas** and **Maktabs** became centers of learning.\n- Subjects like Arabic, Persian, Islamic theology, law, and literature were taught.\n- Higher education institutions like **Aligarh** and **Delhi** became centers of Islamic learning.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Women\u2019s Education**\n- Women\u2019s education was limited and varied across regions and communities.\n- In some cases, women from royal or upper-class families received education in literature, music, and the arts.\n- However, societal norms often restricted formal education for women.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Decentralized and Community-Based**\n- Education was not centralized but rather organized at the community level.\n- Temples, mosques, and local institutions played a significant role in imparting education.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Oral Tradition**\n- Much of the knowledge, especially in rural areas, was preserved and transmitted orally.\n- Storytelling, folklore, and religious discourses were important means of education.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Higher Education Centers**\n- Ancient universities like **Nalanda**, **Takshashila**, **Odantapuri**, and **Vikramashila** were centers of advanced learning.\n- These institutions attracted scholars from across the world and offered courses in philosophy, medicine, astronomy, and more.\n\n---\n\n### **Key Features of Pre-Colonial Education**\n- **Focus on holistic development**: Education was not just intellectual but also moral and spiritual.\n- **Diversity**: Different systems coexisted, catering to various communities and regions.\n- **Practicality**: Vocational skills were emphasized alongside theoretical knowledge.\n- **Accessibility**: While education was not universal, systems like Buddhist monasteries and madrasas were more inclusive.\n\n---\n\nThe British colonial rule later introduced a more formal, centralized, and Westernized education system, which significantly altered the traditional Indian education framework. However, the pre-colonial system laid the foundation for India\u2019s rich intellectual and cultural heritage.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
